<div id="review_253366908" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/253366908" />
    <a title="Manray9" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7288965-manray9"><img alt="Manray9" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518315005p2/7288965.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/253366908?book_show_action=true">Dec 30, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manray9" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manray9" href="/user/show/7288965-manray9">Manray9</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7288965-manray9?shelf=naval-nautical">naval-nautical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7288965-manray9?shelf=wwii-asia">wwii-asia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer253366908" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5208692438150310529">The history of the U. S. Navy contains many stories of great valor -- from Stephen Decatur burning the frigate PHILADELPHIA in the harbor at Tripoli, through David Dixon Porter running the gauntlet of Confederate batteries at Vicksburg, to the attack of Torpedo Squadron 8 at Midway -- but few compare to the actions of USS JOHNSTON and USS HOEL off Samar in 1944. Commander Ernest E. Evans demonstrated the “conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity” worthy of his posthumous Medal of Honor. The sea bat</span>
  <span id="freeText5208692438150310529" style="display:none">The history of the U. S. Navy contains many stories of great valor -- from Stephen Decatur burning the frigate PHILADELPHIA in the harbor at Tripoli, through David Dixon Porter running the gauntlet of Confederate batteries at Vicksburg, to the attack of Torpedo Squadron 8 at Midway -- but few compare to the actions of USS JOHNSTON and USS HOEL off Samar in 1944. Commander Ernest E. Evans demonstrated the “conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity” worthy of his posthumous Medal of Honor. The sea battles known collectively as The Battle of Leyte Gulf may have been the U.S. Navy's finest hour. <br /><br />There should always be a USS JOHNSTON, USS HOEL and a USS ERNEST E. EVANS at sea under the flag of the United States. Jim Hornfischer’s book does honor to all the Tin Can sailors. It is genuine Five Star material.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5208692438150310529" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


